The losers remain challengers.
HARARE: Before this month's presidential elections, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections would have had serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and across the entire southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe have not gotten it.
Instead, they received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were subjected to intimidations, harassments, and threats from Robert Mugabe's party, the Zimbabwe African National Union – Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is state-subsidized terrorism in Africa.
The ZANU terror can be attributed to the rogue elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
A consequence of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), failed to reach the electorate in large parts, especially in rural areas.
In addition, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Because there weren't enough polling stations overall, I believe more than 360,000 people were left standing in line in Harare and Chitungwiza, unable to cast their ballots.
I continue to question the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented the MDC from deploying poll observers at 52% of the rural polling stations.
At the end of the voting, our party was missing observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to impose their will at these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all polling stations that were controlled solely by ZANU supporters.
At our initial investigations, even at this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential election, from which the incumbent President Robert Mugabe emerged victorious with 56% of the 3 million cast votes.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is, in their eyes, illegitimate.
The people of Zimbabwe were deprived of their right to freely and democratically choose their elected president.
The battle over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is above 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and resolute, and they deserve to have this recognized.
It may still be too late.
I write this text in dismay, for Mugabe's regime continues to disregard the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a faithful servant and see this path through with them.
Possibly the government will have me arrested.
I was also arrested beforehand on charges of treason before the elections.
In the worst-case scenario, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the people's will, their rights, and their power.
It lies in our hands to bring about a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overwhelm us.
The democratic change is unstoppable.
But we must be prepared to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I implore the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to see through to the end what we have collectively started.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who refused to be chased away.
It is the heroes of a new Zimbabwe whose voice must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very rocky road together to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the annals of human history, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to preserve their kindness and exuberance.
I can sense that the people of Zimbabwe are impatient.
I understand that.
But for a political process to be possible, they must be patient and wait.
They cannot simply allow these elections to stand, but they must also not fall into the provocation of Mugabe and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the justice system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that across Africa, people are cheated during elections.
In most African states, irregularities, fraud, and deceit appear to be a normal part of elections.
In Africa, there is always somewhere a crisis over elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it is time to allow the people to exercise their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons from our experience for Africa and the world.
My people are in their darkest hour.
I promise not to leave it.
